{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"30e78ca8-ff5a-4624-aff2-a5b76cdc193a","content":"Use `dotnet watch test` — it re-runs your tests automatically whenever you save a file:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\nThe `--filter` flag scopes it to just your failing test for faster feedback. Once it's green, remove the filter to run the full suite.\n\n**The bug:** `RemoveStock` doesn't validate — it happily goes negative instead of throwing. You'll need to add a bounds check in `RemoveStock` to throw an `InvalidOperationException` when `quantity` exceeds available stock.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"43a6fec0-c80f-45bf-8db7-d0b21d4d919b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for their test project. Since this is using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (as indicated by the global.json), they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test`.\n\nLet me check what's available. With .NET 10 and Microsoft.Testing.Platform, `dotnet test --hotreload` should be available. Also `dotnet watch test` works.\n\nThe best approach for rapid iteration is `dotnet watch test` which will re-run tests whenever files change. Let me suggest that.\n\nActually, with .NET 10 and the Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner, they can use:\n\n\n- `dotnet watch test` to automatically re-run tests on file changes\n- `dotnet test --filter` when they need to run specific tests\n\nI should just give them the command since that's what they're asking for.","outputTokens":356},"id":"3999f6bb-f16b-4ece-a8aa-567c8d00b2cf","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:44:56.884Z","parentId":"fcd11f18-ac9d-4ef0-90dc-da1b7f8a9184"}
